series.scopeAndContentNote: This series consists of correspondence, reports, and other records concerning the banking business, world economic conditions, and the role of the Bank of Taiwan, Ltd. of New York in international trade. The records were created and maintained by the Bank of Taiwan, Ltd. of New York. This series includes papers relating to the business of foreign branches of the bank such as minutes of meetings and correspondence, foreign news summaries, Department of State press releases dealing with Japanese-American trade, records of the Japanese Embassy in Washington regarding trade, papers of the National Foreign Trade Council and the American-Japanese Trade Council, reports of the Japanese Chamber of Commerce, regulations of the Federal Reserve Board, reports to the Federal Reserve Bank of New York, and correspondence regarding the business of the New York Agency. This series also includes pamphlets, reports, balance sheets, circulars, letters, and correspondence concerning topics such as currency, loans, workmen's compensation, insurance, and financial matters. Approximately one-third of these records are in the Japanese language.

This series consists of memorandums, airgrams, instructions, narrative and statistical reports, newspaper clippings, photographs, posters, and publications such as pamphlets and newsletters documenting the organization and implementation of the information program at various U.S. information centers and libraries throughout Asia. Countries documented in this series include Australia, Burma, Cambodia, China (to 1949), Indonesia, Japan, Korea, Laos, Malaysia (including Singapore), New Zealand, the Philippines, Taiwan, Thailand, Vietnam, and Western Samoa.

Topics of the records include staffing, cultural cooperation activities, American studies programs, and public opinion regarding the U.S. information program. Included in this series are copies of shipment notices and requisitions for books and periodicals for various information centers; photographs of the interiors of various information centers, showing their usage by the public; and posters for special events at information centers, including several exhibits held at the Burma-America Institute in Rangoon in 1952. These records were maintained by the Cultural Operations Division, Far East Libraries and Centers Branch and its predecessors.

series.scopeAndContentNote:
This series consists chiefly of reports, catalogues, bibliographies, gazetteers, and technical manuals compiled by the Geology Branch for the Office of the Chief Engineer, General Headquarters, Far Eastern Command, translating and summarizing Japanese geological literature.  The subjects include mineral and fuel resources, terrain studies, soil surveys, geophysical-research methods, and related geologic studies.  Some of the reports were prepared with the assistance of the Soil Conservation Service of the Department of Agriculture.  There are also processed monographs concerning water supplies, harbor development, and the construction of airstrips and storage depots.  Geographic areas addressed include Ryukyu-Retto, the northern Ryukyus, Okinawa, the Palau Islands, the Mariana Islands, Formosa (Taiwan), and Japan.  Some reports include maps and copies of photographs.

There are similar reports on areas in Korea, the Aleutian Islands, and Germany.

Also included is a file consisting of questionnaires, correspondence, notes, and manuscript reports concerning water supplies for cities in Japan.

The series includes records of family planning research activities in Bangladesh, Bolivia, Brazil, Chile, Côte d'Ivoire, Egypt, Guatemala, Haiti, Indonesia, Kenya, Korea, Madagascar, Mexico, Morocco, Nepal, Nicaragua, Nigeria, Sri Lanka, Sudan, Taiwan, Tanzania, Thailand, Togo, Tunisia, Yugoslavia, and Zambia.

This series contains memorandums, agreements, correspondence, reports, authorization documents, agendas, copies of electronic mail, newsletters, faxes, vouchers, and other forms maintained by the Secretariat for U.S.-Asia Environmental Partnership (US-AEP). The main correspondents include the American Consulting Engineers Council (ACEC), the ACEC Research and Management Foundation (ACEC/RMF), the World Wildlife Fund, the USAID Bureau of Global Programs, the Office of Program Development and Strategic Planning, the Biodiversity Conservation Network (BCN), the California Environmental Protection Agency, the National Pollution Prevention Roundtable (NPPR), Tata Energy and Resources Institute (TERI), the USAID Office of Energy and the Environment, and the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service (FWS).

Subjects covered include the BCN, the Biodiversity Support Program (BSP), the Asia Pacific Roundtable on Cleaner Production (APRCP), the Environment Exchange Program (EEP), the Environment Support Project, the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species, strategic objective implementation reviews, and site visits. Other topics include projects in other countries focused on promoting environmental infrastructures, ecology, housing, finances, water supplies, waste management, the development of enterprises with community based biodiversity, conservation, agriculture, forest products industry, timber, ecotourism, solving environmental problems in Asia, control of the trade of endangered species, and the creation of international relationships with the private sectors and engineering associations.  The subjects focus overall on Asian countries including Thailand, Indonesia, the Philippines, Malaysia, Singapore, Hong Kong, Taiwan, Korea, India, Sri Lanka, Nepal, and Bangladesh.

series.scopeAndContentNote:
This series consists of ground-level and aerial reconnaisance views of areas in Greece, Albania, Bulgaria, China, Iran, Korea, Turkey, and Taiwan. The purpose of these photographs was to test a new 100-inch focal length camera, manufactured by the Simmon Brothers, for use by the Army. The tests went by the name "Project Muleback 100". Beginning in 1954, Signal Corps photographic teams tested the camera and its improved verstions for use in aerial reconnaisance and ground-level missions. Most of the images were taken with infrared film. Copies of the reports for each mission apparently went to the Office of the Chief Signal Officer and to the Army Staff.

Included in this series is a copy of the first report for "Project Muleback 100", describing the operation of the camera during its use along the Greek-Albanian border in late 1954. This report is found in box 1. Other reports relating to these photographs may be found in the RG 319 decimal files under number 413.53 (Photographic Equipment). These files are in the custody of the Archives' Textual Projects Division.

Captions for these photographs include the date of the photograph, map coordinates of the location photographed, and brief descriptions of the area (giving names of rivers or towns). Original negatives for these prints are found in RG 111, Series SC (refer to the "SC" number on the back of each print).

series.scopeAndContentNote:
This series consists of correspondence, notes, memoranda, reports, lists, legal papers, financial statements, and other records relating to vested bank assets and their liquidation.  The records were maintained by the Legal and Legislative Section and its predecessors.  The records relate primarily to Japanese banks with branches in California, Hawaii, New York, and Washington State.  The banks include Sumitomo Bank, Yokohama Specie Bank, Pacific Bank, Mitsubishi Bank, Mitsui Bank, Bank of Chosen, and the Bank of Taiwan.  Records relating to insurance companies are also included.  The correspondence in the series is between the regional and main offices of the Alien Property Custodian (APC), and later, the Office of Alien Property (OAP), as well as with the Superintendent of Banks, for the state California, New York State, and their legal representatives.  The law firm of Shirley, Robb, and Saroyan was the representative of the California Superintendent for Banks.

Also included are records relating to claims, petitions, and litigation made against the banks, the superintendents, and the OAP to retrieve frozen assets on behalf of companies and individuals.  This includes claims by a Buddhist temple as well as motion picture companies in Los Angeles.  Also included are audits, inventories, balance sheets, and liquidation statements for the banks.

This series consists of airgrams, correspondence, despatches, instructions, memoranda, notes, proposals, publications, reports, telegrams, and travel itineraries relating to several Armed Forces International Nutrition Conferences organized and/or attended by members of the Interdepartmental Committee on Nutrition for National Defense (ICNND). 

The series includes documentation on the following Armed Forces International Nutrition Conferences: Ankara, Turkey, April 14-16, 1958 (Second Conference); Rawalpindi, Pakistan, October 19-24, 1959 (Third Conference); Washington, D.C., and Denver, Colorado, August 24-31, 1960 (Fourth Conference); and Madrid, Spain, April 24-30, 1962 (Fifth Conference). The Fourth Conference took place in conjunction with the Fifth International Nutrition Congress, Washington, D.C., September 1-7, 1960. Similarly the series includes documentation on the First Far East Symposium on Nutrition, Saigon, Vietnam, March 11-16, 1962; the Second Far East Symposium on Nutrition, Taipei, Taiwan, May 18-25, 1964; and the Third Far East Symposium on Nutrition, Manila, Philippines, January 23-30, 1967. The Conferences were attended by delegations from the United States and many other countries. Information is also included on visits by Conference attendees to medical and dental facilities in the conference host cities and other locations. Conference topics included nutrition, and other medical and dental research and related issues. Further, the series also includes the proceedings of the Fifth Armed Forces International Nutrition Conference, Madrid, Spain, April, 1962, along with the complete address to the Conference by Dr. Frank M. Berry, Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense (Manpower - Health and Medical), and Chairman, ICNND.

A least two documents are written in Spanish and one is written in German.

series.scopeAndContentNote:
This series is composed of three subsets: Total, Rural, and Urban Population Counts and projections. The Rural and Total subsets use a rectangular grid of cells (representing a part of the earth's surface) for mapping. Each cell is 20 minutes of latitude by 30 minutes of longitude (about 2,000 square kilometers at the equator). Accordingly, there are six cells in a square degree. The location of each cell is identified by the latitude and longitude of its center point. The Total Population files are ready to be imported into ARC/INFO as polygon coverages. 

For urban areas of more than 25,000 people, density circles are drawn to provide more detail. The density circles cover built-up urban areas for 89 countries.  An urban area covered by circles ("agglomeration") has a minimum of 25,000 people and at least 95 percent of the population covered by circles.  A circle's maximum radius is 2.0 nautical miles; the minimum radius is 0.3 nautical miles.  The location of a circle is identified by the latitude and longitude of its center.  All countries have cells; if a country is small or very rural, it might not have any circles.

Areas for which population projections and/or mapping data are available include: Algeria, American Samoa, Angola, Antigua and Barbuda, Australia, The Bahamas, Barbados, Belgium, Belize, Bermuda, Bolivia, Canada, Cape Verde, Chad, Comoros, Cook Islands, Costa Rica, Croatia, Cyprus, Dominica, Dominican Republic, Egypt, El Salvador, Falkland Islands, Fiji, Finland French Guiana, The Gambia, Germany, Grenada, Guadeloupe, Guam, Guatemala, Guyana, Haiti, Honduras, Hong Kong, Iceland, Iraq, Ireland, Italy, Jamaica, Japan, Kenya, Kiribati, Lesotho, Libya, Luxembourg, Macedonia, Malawi, Mali, Malta, Malaysia, Martinique, Mauritius, Mexico, Monaco, Morocco, Netherlands, New Caledonia, New Zealand, Nicaragua, Norfolk Island, Norway, Oman, Panama, Papua New Guinea, Paraguay, Phillippines,  Pitcairn Islands, Portugal, Puerto Rico, Qatar, Saint Lucia, Saint Pierre and Miquelon, Saint Vincent and the Grenadines, Saudi Arabia, Senegal, Serbia, Singapore, Solomon Islands, South Africa, South Korea, Spain, Suriname, Svalbard, Swaziland, Sweden, Syria, Taiwan, Tanzania, Thailand, Tokelau, Trinidad and Tobago, Tunisia, Turkey, Tuvalu, United States, Uruguay, Vanuatu, Venezuela, Virgin Islands, Wake Island, Western Samoa, Zaire, Zambia, and Zimbabwe.

series.scopeAndContentNote: This series consists of correspondence, including letters, circulars, dispatches, reports, memorandums, orders, and telegrams pertaining to high level policymaking and planning in the Far East Command (FEC or FECom).  The chief focus is on FEC efforts to provide military assistance and advice to countries within its area of responsibility, namely the Republic of Korea, the Republic of China, the Republic of Vietnam, Laos, Japan and the Philippine Islands.  The documents chart the development and progress of the militaries in those countries, as well as cover their political situations.  Topics include the Binh Xuyen and Cao Dai movements in South Vietnam, the development of the Japanese and Korean defense industries, and the status of forces on the Korean Peninsula.  American and allied efforts to prepare the defenses of FEC countries from internal, conventional and nuclear threats are discussed in depth, as well as the operations of Mutual Defense Assistance Programs (MDAP's), Military Assistance Advisory Groups (MAAG's), and Joint United States Military Assistance Groups (JUSMAG's).  Correspondence from General Lyman L. Lemnitzer, General Matthew B. Ridgway, General Maxwell D. Taylor, and Admiral Robert B. Carney is included.
